xcrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":13,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":26,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":35,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":80,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Combes was born in 1302, in Gittisham, Devon, England, his father, Sir Neil Combe, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Neil Combe, was 20. He married Mrs. William de Combes in 1327, in Gittisham, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Gittisham, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1302–":"1302–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1307–Female":"1307–Surnud","1332–1400":"1332–1400","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1282":"1282","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Manor Of Gittisham, Gittisham, Devon, England":"Gittisham, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gittisham, Devon, England":"Gittisham, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1302–":"1302–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1307–Female":"1307–Kuollut","1332–1400":"1332–1400","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1282":"1282","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Manor Of Gittisham, Gittisham, Devon, England":"Gittisham, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gittisham, Devon, England":"Gittisham, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1302–":"1302–Décédé","1302–Male":"1302–Décédé","1307–Female":"1307–Décédée","1332–1400":"1332–1400","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1282–Female":"1282–Décédée","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1282":"1282","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","131